t 1592":"circa 1592","Weymouth, Dorset, England":"Weymouth, Dorset, England","England":"England"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1580–Female":"1580–Deceased","1592–1656":"1592–1656","1606–1642":"1606–1642","1612–1672":"1612–1672","1616–1692":"1616–1692","–Male":"Deceased","29 February 1612":"29 February 1612","1692":"1692","1592":"1592","1580":"1580","about 1606":"about 1606","1689":"1689","1612":"1612","1656":"1656","1688":"1688","about 1616":"about 1616","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1642":"1642","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1672":"1672","1606":"1606","1616":"1616","about 1592":"about 1592","Weymouth, Dorset, England":"Weymouth, Dorset, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly southern and southwestern): from Middle English <i>frie</i> ‘free’ (Old English <i>frīo</i>, <i>frīg</i>), with reference either to rank or tenurial status (‘free-born’) or to character (‘generous, open-handed’). It is synonymous with   Free  .","Americanized form of German   Frei   or   Frey  , or of the Dutch cognate <b>Vrij</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Frye","meanings":["English: variant of   Fry  .","North German: variant of   Frey  .","History: Joseph Frye (1711/12–94) was a military officer from Andover, MA, where the family had long been of local prominence. In 1762, he was granted a township in ME, later named Fryeburg after him, and moved his family there. His great-great-grandson William Pierce Frye was born in Lewiston, ME, and served in Congress, first as a member of the House of Representatives and then the Senate from 1871 until his death in 1911."]},{"name":"Free","meanings":["English: nickname or status name from Middle English <i>fre</i> ‘free’ (Old English <i>frēo</i>), with reference to either tenurial status (‘free born’) or to character (‘noble, generous, open-handed’).","Irish: variant of   Freeman  .","Americanized form of Swiss German and German   Frei   and   Frey  ."]}]},{"name":"Mr.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name from <i>mór</i> ‘large, great’. This was the commonest of all girls’ names in late medieval Ireland, and has continued in use in both Ireland and Scotland to the present day."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":5,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":7,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":40,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705213,"age":62,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","descripti